Default imputation efficiency comparision

Authors: Jakub Pingielski, Paulina Przybyek, Renata Rlkiewicz, Jakub Winiewski (Warsaw University of Technology)

Abstract

Imputation of missing values is one the most common reprocessing steps when working with many real-life datasets. Most popular strategies are filling missing data with median or mode value. They are easy to implement and fast to compute, but this naive approach might not lead to best model performance. In contrast, more sophisticated procedures e.g.using tree-based models, can result in better models, but adds additional algorithmic complexity and computational costs to the training procedure.
Our experiment involves comparing imputation techniques and assessing which techniques are better: naive or more advanced. We analyzed both these methods on 11 binary classification datasets from OpenML repository and presented imputations effect on four different measures of model performance: Area Under the Curve (AUC), geometric mean of sensitivity and specificity, Balanced Accuracy and Weighted TPR-TNR1.

Introduction and Motivation

Data is becoming more and more useful and valuable in various industries. Companies started to gather data on scale that has not been imagined before. But with more data comes more problems. One of them is missing values. Omitting observations affected by them is one way, but why doing it while the information that they posses may be still valuable? This is why imputation of missing values is essential when dealing with real life data. But there is various methods of imputation and for inexperienced user it might be confusing and hard to decide which one to use. It may be even harder to design metrics that allow to compare methods between them. Sometimes omitting rows or even removing columns and NA can give satisfying results but in majority of time it is worse than simple imputation methods. For simple tasks mean/median and mode are fast and computationally efficient and can give good results. But they have no variance and because of that can give worse results on complex datasets than more robust methods. On the other hand random forests and decision trees are in theory more accurate but it takes more valuable time for them to give an answer. Deciding which one of them is the best for inexperienced user is the purpose of this article. We are benchmarking methods that have different complexity from various packages along with simple imputation methods but without parameter tuning, so that casual user can benefit from it. The default methods from packages are easy to use and despite not living up to their potential they give more than acceptable results.

Methodology

We analyzed nine different imputing strategies:

  1. removing columns with missing values
  2. imputing with random values from given feature
  3. imputing with median (for numerical features) and mode (for categorical features)
  4. imputing with Random Forests (using missForest2 package)
  5. imputing with k-Nearest Neighbour Imputation based on a variation of the Gower Distance (using VIM3 package)
  6. imputing with sequential, random (within a domain) hot-deck algorithm (using VIM package)
  7. imputing with Iterative Robust Model-Based Imputation (IRMI) (using VIM package)
  8. imputing with Fully Conditional Specification and predictive mean matching (using mice4 package)
  9. imputing with Fully Conditional Specification and classification and regression trees (using mice package)

First three methods are self-explanatory and do not have any tuning hyperparameters. In contrast, algorithms provided in missForest, VIM and mice packages are complex and may require costly hyperparameters tuning. We used default implementations in our experiments, based on the assumption that data imputation is only a small step in data modelling process and additional complexity and more hyperparameters might create too steep learning curve for your average data scientist to even bother with these methods.

Since neither mlr nor caret package enable using custom imputing methods in your modelling pipeline, the only way to avoid data leakage was to impute values separately for train and test datasets. This imposes severe limitation on our imputation effectiveness, especially for small datasets, since information learned during imputing values in training data set cannot be used during test set imputation.

Having that caveat in mind, we performed aforementioned imputing methods for 11 datasets from OpenML repository. Since all datasets were binary classification problems and many of them were heavily imbalanced, we used 4 metrics to evaluate our models performance:

Classifier Evaluation Measures
Measure Formula
AUC Measures area under plot of Sensitivity against Specificity
Balanced Accuracy \(\frac{1}{2}(Sensitivity+Specificity)\)
Geometric Mean \(\sqrt{Sensitivity*Specificity}\)
Weighted TPR-TNR \((Sensitivity*\frac{N}{P+N})+(Specificity*\frac{P}{P+N})\)

Area under ROC curve (AUC) is used as a general performance metrics, while the rest is used to specifically evaluate model performance on imbalanced data sets.
Accuracy measures how good model is in corectly predicting both positive and negative cases. If your dataset is imbalanced, then regular accuracy may not be enough (cost of misclassification of minority class instance is higher than for majority class instance). That is why we use Balanced Accuracy, which is the arythmetic mean of the TPR (Sensitivity) and FPR (Specificity).
Geometric Mean (of Sensitivity and Specificity) is a metric that measures the balance between classification performances on both the majority and minority classes.
Weighted TPR-TNR is a very promising new single valued measure for classification. It takes into account the imbalance ratio of the dataset and assign different weights to the TPR and TNR (where P is total number of positive cases and N is total number of negative cases).

All models were based on classifiers from caret5 package with AUC being the summary metric that was used to select the optima addl model. Our goal was to use classification models that are as different from each other as possible, to check if model complexity and flexibility have impact on effectiveness of imputation strategy. Selected classification algorithms are listed below.

  1. Bagged CART - simple classification trees with bootstrap aggregation
  2. Random Forest - very flexible, robust and popular algorith, with no assumptions about data
  3. Multivariate Adaptive Regression Spline - assumes that relation between features and response can be expressed by combining two linear models at certain cutoff point - can be regarded as a model with flexibility between linear and nonlinear models
  4. k-Nearest Neighbors - assumes that similar observations are close to each other in feature space, assumes very local impact of features
  5. Naive Bayes - nonlinear model with assumption that all features are independent from each other

In addition to registering model metrics for each imputation technique we also saved imputation time, since even the best imputation method is useless if it takes to long to perform.

Results

Experiment

In the experiment we used 5 different classification algorithms and 11 different datasets to assess performance of the imputation of missing values using the previously described measures. The information about these datasets is given in the table below.

Datasets Information
Dataset Number of observations Number of features Imbalanced ratio Percent of missing values

hepatitis 155 20 3.843750 5.387

echoMonths 130 10 1.031250 7.462

The caret package in R programming was used to conduct the experiment. Classification algorithms used in this experiment were: ranger, earth, treebag, knn, nb existing in function train() from this package.

The procedure followed to assess performance of the imputation of missing values was as follows:

  1. The dataset was divided into training and test subsets with split percentage of 80 and 20 percent respectively.
  2. We imputed values separately for train and test datasets. This process was repeated for all nine different imputing strategies. During this process, data imputation time was measured.
  3. All imputed train and test datasets were used in the five classification algorithms.
  4. The classifiers were built using train datasets.
  5. The classification results were obtained using test datasets.

Before dividing into training and test subsets and building classifiers, seed equal to one was set.

Imputation results

Before analizing results, two caveats:

  1. some of our datasets were quite small, with 100 or so observations
  2. some of our datasets were heavily imbalanced

Thus, results might not be robust and furhter investigation into optimal imputing methods might be required.

While analysing the results we are looking at 2 things:

  1. for which imputation method the metrics have the best results.
  2. time of imputation.

Especially for big datasets, using sophisticated imputation methods reguires many hours or even days of computing what make them inefficient.

Ranking of results

Each model has its specific features and might be thriving after applying different imputation methods. Seeing which method was the best (and the worst) for each model sholud give more wide perspective. For creating ranking only Weighted TPR-TNR will be taken into consideration. Rank feature here is average of ranks from all datasets so if some imputation was second in the metric it would be given rank 2. If two imputations had the same values in the metric they would both have the same rank. NA is always treated as the last one.

Top 3 best imputations for each model

nb random fill vim knn missForest

Random fill is the best in 3 out of 5 models. For ranger and knn the best are VIM knn and missForest respectively. In our top 3 ranking also appears median and mode and two mice methods - pmm and cart.

Now lets see top 3 worst imputations.

Removing columns is the worst choice when imputing data, which is not surprising. It removes vital information from data resulting in significantly worse performance. Second from the end is almost for all models vim irmi.

Other methods are seen in boxplots below.

Random fill is the best method but median of ranks is the same as in missForest and median and mode imputation. Second worst imputation method is vim irmi.

Similarity of imputations

To see how similar are imputations to each other we used biplot. Biplot is using PCA to reduce dimensionality of the data in our case of results. If imputation names are close to each other, it means that they produce similar results. If arrows are close to each other metrics are correlated. Data came from our imputation results for all models without NA values. Then for each imputation data was averaged and processed by PCA.

Performance metrics are highly correlated. Remove columns method is the most unique method. VIMs methods although closer with respect to PC1 (which is more important) are not as similar as cart or simpler imputation methods in term of results.

Imputation time

In imputation not only results matter. While having small dataset imputation time is not something worth considering. But when having tens or hundreds of thousands observations some more complex imputations might take really long time. In this case maximum samples in data is 5000 but diferences are already visible.

Mean time
Average results - time
imputation_name Time
remove columns 0.0140457
random fill 0.0153626
median and mode 0.0271520
vim hotdeck 0.2484076
vim knn 1.6832855
pmm (mice) 8.1866904
missForest 8.9693506
vim irmi 10.1300411
cart (mice) 20.0550151

As one might predicted, imputation with mean and mode removing columns or filling NAs with random value are fastests methods. Imputations from VIM package also have small computation time. Imputing with missForest package or using predictive mean matching in mice package is more than 1000 times slower, whilst using cart instead of pmm in mice package additionaly increases computation time more than threefold.

Distribution of time

Imputation time shown in shape of boxplots. Clear distinction between mice, missForest and VIM irmi packages functions which are significantly slower than other methods. On contrary here imputation time was taken into consideration even when NAs were produced.

Influence of amount of NA on time

Time needed to process NAs is very volatile. For simple imputation methods and VIMs hotdeck time needed compared to the rest of imputations seems to be constant. This plot was achieved by getting information from datasets and imputing. Volatality might be effect of different data types, number of factors, continous varaibles distribution, CPU usage by ethernal programs etc. In future our team will measure time few times to then average results increasing their reliability.

Summary and conclusions

Our experiments have unexpected results - it turns out that using naive strategy of imputing with random values resulted in models with the best performance. Reason of poor performance of more complex imputation methods might be the fact that we used default values of hyperparameters and some tuning may be required to show full potential of these methods. Some datasets were simple and small therefore imputation with more robust methods could be insingificant. What we did prove was that simple imputation methods might still be valuable despite their aparent flaws. What was significant was big overhead that simple imputations had in terms of results achieved in time. While having big dataset with limited number of missing values they might be the best solution because some methods use whole data to train its missing value imputation.
We might not ignore huge computational overhead that is the result of using complex computing methods. The point of this paper was to test those methods for inexperienced users and find the most valuable one for them. As for now considering both performance and time the best are random fill, median and mode and VIMs hotdeck. They all achieve satysfying results, are reliable and work for every dataset. One have to think twice before using them and ask him or herself: why do I even bother? and use simple imputation instead.
